WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.440 --> 00:00:12.200
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. We are now&nbsp;
starting to talk about algebra in this series&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:18.840
on foundational aspects of mathematics, and today&nbsp;
we're going to talk about a rather important step&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:25.880
up from linear equations: quadratic equations,&nbsp;
which have a very long and illustrious history.

00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:33.760
So the basic problem is something like this:&nbsp;
suppose that we have the equation x^2 = 49.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:42.080
What does x^2 mean? It means x * x, okay?&nbsp;
That's called the squaring operation. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:47.880
we'd like to know what is the solution&nbsp;
to this equation. What can x be? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:52.880
if you know your multiplication table, you'll&nbsp;
know that 7 * 7 is 49, so there's the solution&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.880 --> 00:01:00.280
x = 7. But if you think about it for a little&nbsp;
while, you'll also realize that -7 is also a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:08.080
solution because -7 * -7 is also 49. So if we're&nbsp;
going to allow negative numbers—and we don't have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:15.960
to—but if we are going to, then there's&nbsp;
actually two solutions: x = 7 and x = -7.

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:22.560
Now for this kind of quadratic equation, knowing&nbsp;
what the squares are is very useful. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:27.320
something that probably most public school&nbsp;
students haven't seen, but it's a good thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:32.800
for them to see. They don't have to memorize it,&nbsp;
but they should have at least seen this table of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:38.960
squares up to a certain amount. So here I've&nbsp;
shown you what they all are: probably from 1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:46.360
up to 100. It's familiar, maybe 11 squared, 12&nbsp;
squared, familiar. But then 13 squared is 169,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:56.600
14 squared is 196, 15 squared is 225, 16 squared&nbsp;
is 256, 17 squared is 289, 18 squared is 324,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.600 --> 00:02:06.040
19 squared is 361, 20 squared is 400, 100 squared&nbsp;
is 10,000. Those are all useful values to know.

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:13.600
But what if we're given a bigger equation&nbsp;
like x^2 = 6,084? How did I get 6,084? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:20.160
I took the number 78 and I squared it. So this is&nbsp;
an easy way of generating a quadratic equation:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:25.640
you take some number, you square it, and&nbsp;
then you give your friend this equation. Say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.640 --> 00:02:32.800
"What is x^2 equals blah blah blah?" You know&nbsp;
because you've taken a number and squared it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:41.040
but for him to unravel that operation might be a&nbsp;
little bit tricky. So we're going to try to think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:46.640
about this kind of quadratic equation&nbsp;
and some more general variants of it.

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:51.360
But before we do, let's have a look&nbsp;
at some general laws which are very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:58.480
pertinent to understanding quadratic equations.&nbsp;
The first is what happens when we square x + 1:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:04.800
(x + 1)^2. So that's (x + 1) * (x + 1).&nbsp;
If we use the distributive law here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:11.880
there's an x here and another x here&nbsp;
for a total of 2x, and then there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:20.920
also a +1. So a very important equation or&nbsp;
identity is that (x + 1)^2 is x^2 + 2x + 1.

00:03:20.920 --> 00:03:25.240
This is important because, first of all, it&nbsp;
allows us to generate this table a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:30.600
bit more efficiently than squaring each&nbsp;
individual number. For example, suppose we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:37.520
know that 20^2 is 400 and we want to know what is&nbsp;
21 squared. Well, according to this little rule,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:48.600
it's 20^2 + 2 * 20 which is 40 + 1. So to&nbsp;
go from here to here, we just take this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:55.680
add two times the value here which is 20, and&nbsp;
add one. Similarly, to go from here to here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.680 --> 00:04:02.600
we take this number, add two times that, which&nbsp;
would be 42. We add that, and we get 483, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:12.000
we add one more to get 484. That's a somewhat&nbsp;
faster way of generating a table like this.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.800
This identity has an important generalization&nbsp;
when we replace the one with a general y:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:30.920
(x + y)^2. All students of algebra learn that this&nbsp;
is x^2 + 2xy + y^2. Here we're already seeing a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:38.640
kind of change in our use of the variables x and&nbsp;
y. When I write down this equation, I'm no longer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:46.120
thinking of x and y as unknown quantities. I'm&nbsp;
rather thinking of them as representing arbitrary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:52.200
or general numbers. So it's no longer a question&nbsp;
of having a look at this and saying what is x,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.200 --> 00:05:01.680
what is y. x and y are not mystery numbers. This&nbsp;
is a general law that applies to any x and any y.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:07.720
It's a slightly different usage of the letters&nbsp;
x and y. We'll keep that in mind for later.

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:16.840
So here's a more general quadratic equation:&nbsp;
x^2 + 10x = 39. x is some mystery number that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:23.000
satisfies this equation, and I want you to tell&nbsp;
me what x is. Well, you can try trial and error,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.840
try x = 1, try x = 2, and so on until&nbsp;
eventually you'll get it. In this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:33.400
it's not too hard, but a general strategy&nbsp;
for solving this kind of equation has been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:39.960
known by many cultures. So the ancient&nbsp;
Chinese, the Babylonians, the Arabs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:48.760
the Hindus—they all had ideas of how to solve this&nbsp;
kind of equation. In particular, Al-Khwarizmi,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:55.920
who we mentioned before around 800 AD, had&nbsp;
the following rather nice interpretation.

00:05:55.920 --> 00:06:05.800
So we think of an L-shaped figure like this, where&nbsp;
this has side x (whatever x is) and this has side&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:13.600
five. Here, symmetrically, x and five. We're&nbsp;
thinking now about the area of this L-shaped&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:23.360
region. There's an x^2 here for that square,&nbsp;
and each of these rectangles has area 5x. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:30.120
altogether, the area is x^2 + 10x because we&nbsp;
have two of these rectangles. That's exactly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:37.640
the left-hand side. Now what we do is we&nbsp;
think about completing this diagram to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:43.000
square. In other words, these dotted lines&nbsp;
here—we add another portion so that now we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:50.280
have a complete square. Once we've done that,&nbsp;
we have a square whose side is x + 5. So this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.280 --> 00:06:58.240
total area here will be (x + 5)^2, and that's&nbsp;
going to be the area that we started with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:04.400
which we're assuming is 39, plus the area of&nbsp;
the square that we've added. What is the area&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.400 --> 00:07:12.880
of the square that we've added? Well,&nbsp;
it's 5 by 5, so this area here is 25.

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:24.560
So (x + 5)^2, the entire area here, is 39 + 25,&nbsp;
which we work out is 64. Now the equation has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:32.120
been transformed from an equation like this to&nbsp;
the equation (x + 5)^2 = 64. This is very much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:35.840
like the simpler kind of equation that we've&nbsp;
already been talking about. Its solution is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:48.600
x + 5 = 8 because 8 * 8 is 64. From that, we&nbsp;
can deduce that x = 8 - 5, which is three.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:55.160
Now there's another solution too because&nbsp;
we could also have chosen -8 as the square&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.160 --> 00:08:10.080
root of 64. So there would be another solution&nbsp;
here obtained by taking -8 - 5, which is -13.

